<span class="displaytext"><b><em>claims fiscal restraint, but would raise taxes to pay for big spending</em></b> <p><b> <em>"our nation cannot afford the (PARTY NAME) and a (PARTY NAME) president like (candidate full) who will sign tax increases into law. instead of following (PARTY NAME), we need to lower taxes, cut spending, and grow the economy."</em> – gov. (candidate full)</b> (gov. (candidate full), press release, 10/25/07) </p><p><b> <u>for sen. (candidate last), fiscal restraint means higher taxes to pay for more spending:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) claims he will bring fiscal restraint to washington.</b> "(candidate last) loves his (PARTY NAME)s. he makes an open pitch for gop voters in his stump speeches, even as he calls them out in his stump speeches, saying he can beat mitt and rudy and (candidate last). ... he went on to contrast himself with all the (PARTY NAME)s in the field, saying he believes in fiscal restraint 'unlike the (PARTY NAME) orthodoxy.'" (aswini anburajan, "(candidate last) contrasts himself with (candidate last)," nbc news' first read, <a href="http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/archive/2007/12/30/539516.aspx">http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/</a>, posted 12/30/07) </p><p><b>but sen. (candidate last) would hike taxes to pay for his health care plan.</b> "(PARTY NAME) presidential hopeful (candidate full) on tuesday offered a plan to provide health care to millions of americans and more affordable medical insurance, financed by tax increases on the wealthy. ... the experts also said (candidate last) could pay for his plan mostly through steps that the candidate already has said he would take -- allowing president bush's tax cuts on dividends and capital gains and on those making more than about $250,000 a year to expire in 2010 instead of acting to make them permanent. the rest of the $65 billion funding could come by raising taxes on inheritances worth more than $7 million. " (mike glover, "taxes on wealthy would rise under (candidate last) health care plan," <em>the associated press</em>, 5/29/07) </p><p align="center"> <b>the (candidate last) vision: "the right answer is always to keep taxes down"</b> </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) rejects the (PARTY NAME)' attempts to raise taxes on american families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that america "can't afford" the (PARTY NAME)' plans to increase taxes.</b> gov. (candidate last): "charlie rangel just came out this week saying he wants to put a surcharge on taxes, largest increase in the history of america. look, more taxes are what the (PARTY NAME) have in mind to fund many of (candidate full)'s million good ideas. we can't afford that. it would slow down the economy. it would kill job creation in this country." (cnbc's "mad money," 10/28/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last): "the right answer is always to keep taxes down."</b> gov. (candidate last): "the right answer is always to keep taxes down. don't add new taxes, but instead allow the american people and the entrepreneurial spirit to grow our economy. that's the best way to get revenues for government and the best ways to get good jobs for our people." (cnbc's "mad money," 10/28/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) opposes the (PARTY NAME)' plans to roll back the bush tax cuts.</b> gov. (candidate last): "let me tell you what i'd do, as opposed to what (candidate full) would do with regard to our tax and spending policies. first of all, i would make the bush tax cuts permanent immediately – all of them, not some of them, but all of them." (gov. (candidate full), remarks to the club for growth, 10/17/07) </p><p align="center"> <b>sen. (candidate last): a tax hike "restores some fairness"</b> </p><p><b> <u>the (PARTY NAME) support raising taxes on american families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate full) (d-il) said that rolling back the bush tax cuts "simply restores some fairness."</b> (candidate last): "those kinds of progressive tax steps, while closing loopholes and rolling back the bush tax cuts to the top 1 percent, simply restores some fairness and a sense that we're all in this together as opposed to each of us being in it on our own." (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) would raise the cap on social security payroll taxes.</b> (candidate last): "i think the best way to approach this is to adjust the cap on the payroll tax so that people like myself are paying a little bit more and people who are in need are protected. that is the option that i will be pushing forward." (nbc's "meet the press," 11/11/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- sen. (candidate last) even supports a tax increase on himself.</b> nbc's tim russert: "a tax increase for some?" (candidate last): "tax increase for people like myself probably." (nbc's "meet the press," 11/11/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>sen. (candidate last) wants americans to pay "a little bit more," even "middle class folks."</b> (candidate last): "so what i've said -- and i know some others on this stage have said -- is that among the options that are available, the best one is to lift the cap on the payroll tax, <u>potentially</u> exempting folks in the middle -- middle-class folks -- but making sure that the wealthy are paying more of their fair share, a little bit more." (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07)</p></span>



